1. Understanding Different Styles of Yoga

23rd July 2025 at 4:57pm
ashtangabikramhathahot yogaiyengarkundalinirestorativeyin yoga

Understanding Different Styles of Yoga

Introduction

Yoga has evolved over thousands of years into what it is today. At its core, yoga maintains its foundational principals and philosophy that have been passed down over the years.

Today there are many types of yoga that all have these common ground principals structured into their style of practice.

People from different backgrounds, cultures, and interests seek out yoga for a variety of reasons.

For example, some students may prefer the spiritual aspect of yoga while others prefer the physical. Similarly, some students may prefer a more calming yoga practice, while others prefer a more rigorous one. All these differences are what truly make yoga such a beautiful and unique practice - giving everyone an opportunity to experience it in their own special way.

Examples

While it’s not important to be a master of all styles of yoga - it is important to understand and be aware of their differences. This allows us to better appreciate and respect the different practices of yogis all over the world. These are just some of the many styles of yoga practiced today:

  • 1.1 Ashtanga yoga
  • 1.2 Hatha yoga
  • 1.3 Hot yoga (Bikram)
  • 1.4 Kundalini yoga
  • 1.5 Iyengar yoga
  • 1.6 Restorative yoga
  • 1.7 Vinyasa yoga
  • 1.8 Yin yoga

1.1 Ashtanga yoga

23rd July 2025 at 4:55pm
ashtanga

Sanskrit

Ashtanga - EIGHT limbs in sanskrit (Ashta + Eight and Anga = limbs)

Pronounce

ASH-taan-ga

Benefits

Increases muscles strength, flexibility, stamina, concentration, and mental clarity.

Overview

Ashtanga Yoga was introduced to the West in the 1970's by yogi Pattabhi Jois

Ashtanga is a rigorous style of yoga with a specific sequence of poses meant to challenge the mind, body, and soul.

Ashtanga Yoga is designed to purify the body and cultivate a deeper connection to the self through asana practice.

Style

Ashtanga classes follow a similar sequence flow to a Vinyasa style class - with the only difference being that Ashtanga is much more rigorous and follows a stricter class sequence.

It has SIX sequences of poses - Primary, Intermediate and FOUR advanced

Primarily teacher-led but could be structured as a MYSORE class. Mysore = "Self-led".

Usually NO PROPS, NO MODIFICATIONS and NO MUSIC

Other Yoga Styles

1.2 Hatha yoga

23rd July 2025 at 4:58pm
hatha

Sanskrit

Hatha = strong, willful, or forceful

Pronounce

Haa-taa

Benefits

Increases strength, balance, flexibility, concentration, and bone density.

Promotes calm and inner peace.

Overview

Hatha Yoga encompasses many general styles of yoga, with a broad definition derived from the ancient yogic texts. While its origin is thousands of years old, it was popularized by Tirumalai Krishnamacharya in the early 20th century.

Through breathing exercises in combination with physical poses, Hatha yoga seeks to cleanse and connect the mind and body. Pranayama and the asanas are the most widely recognized parts of Hatha yoga.

Hatha yoga is rooted in more deeper practices; including yogic lifestyle, meditation, and yogic philosophy.

In Hatha Yoga's original philosophies, pranayama and asanas were meant to achieve a meditative state of oneness with the self.

Popularized by Tirumalai Krishnamacharya in the early 20th century.

Style

In the West, Hatha Yoga encompasses all the other major styles of yoga and is the most common class type offered in Western style yoga classes.

A class that is titled "Hatha" is usually a gentle level class with basic yoga asanas. This type of class would probably not be considered a high energy class, such as a power or hot yoga class. Hatha yoga instead combines the use of deep breathing and different postures to achieve a meditative state.

Link to Optional Yoga Practice - Hatha Yoga with Joe Miller on YouTube (01:00:51).

1.3 Hot yoga (Bikram)

23rd July 2025 at 4:58pm
bikramhot yoga

Sanskrit

No sanskrit word as this is a modern style done in a hot studio

Benefits

  • Regulates metabolism
  • Increases flexibility, immunity, and strength
  • Promotes detoxification of the body

Overview

The Hot Yoga class concept was first introduced by Bikram Choudhury in the 1970s under the title "Bikram Yoga." It is a branded form of hot yoga with a 26 pose sequence done twice per class.

More recent hot yoga has no formal set of poses but is done in a studio at up to 40c. Heat helps to loosen stiff joints and strengthen muscles.

Style

Hot Yoga and Bikram Yoga classes both use heat to aid in loosening stiff joints and strengthening muscles. The flow like sequence of the classes help to promote detoxification of the body through sweating.

Hot yoga follows a Vinyasa style with high energy - listen to your body and stay hydrated in a hot yoga class.

1.4 Kundalini yoga

23rd July 2025 at 4:58pm
kundalini

Sanskrit

Kundalini = "coiled serpent" or "coiled snake"

Pronounce

KOON-duh-LEE-nee

Benefits

  • Increased relaxation, flexibility, and mental clarity
  • Promotes calm and inner peace

Overview

Kundalini Yoga is rooted in Hatha Yoga and is commonly recognized for its spiritual benefits.

Kundalini presents the imagery of a snake coiled at the base of the spine which represents raw untapped energy in our bodies.

This imagery of a coiled snake comes from Hindu philosophy and is first mentioned in the Upanishads.

The objective of this practice is to ‘uncoil’ and activate this energy through a series of poses, pranayama, sounds, and meditation.

In Kundalini Yoga, there's usually a specific focus on meditative yoga poses that relate to the core and lower back.

The asanas are also structured in "kriyas." Kriyas are a set of asanas, pranayama, and mantras connected in a set order to achieve a higher state of consciousness and inner peace.

Kundalini Yoga was popularized among Western audiences through famed yogi Yogi Bhajan. Yogi Bhajan gained national recognition for his translation of ancient yoga philosophies into modern Western morals in the 1960's.

Style

A Kundalini Yoga class is typically structured in the following order;

  • a warm up
  • kriya (a series of asanas, breathing, and sounds),
  • relaxation
  • meditation

Classes are typically opened and closed with a mantra.

1.5 Iyengar yoga

23rd July 2025 at 4:58pm
iyengar

Sanskrit

This style is named after its founder B.K.S. Iyengar - it has no sanskrit equivalent

Benefits

Increases muscular strength, flexibility, stamina, concentration, and mental clarity.

Overview

Iyengar Yoga was founded by B.K.S. Iyengar, one of the key influential figures of yoga during the 20th century.

Iyengar Yoga classes focus on proper alignment and the precise use of teaching cues and language to achieve alignment.

The classes focus on a progressive philosophy that includes basic beginner foundations in early classes. These beginner foundation classes later build upon more advanced classes as students progress in their practice.

Style

Iyengar Yoga classes are structured around gradual progression of the practice over time.

The classes are highly focused on finding proper alignment in each pose and breath connection in the poses.

Iyengar classes also focus on the use of props to perfect alignment for each pose. In Iyengar classes, blankets, straps, blocks, chairs and other props are used frequently to help students understand key alignment principles for poses and for adjusting poses.

Iyengar classes are usually slower pace with the poses being held for longer periods of time.

1.6 Restorative yoga

23rd July 2025 at 4:58pm
restorative

Benefits

Increases flexibility, stamina, concentration, and mental clarity.

Overview

Restorative yoga is rooted in the teachings of Iyengar and was first introduced in the 1970's by Judith Hanson Lasater - a yoga teacher who was a student of Iyengar.

Iyengar recognized the healing power of Restorative yoga to help overcome illness within himself and sought out the use of props to build a more restorative & healing practice.

Restorative yoga classes focus on a slow-paced style originally developed for students recovering from an illness or injury. Restorative yoga is also considered an ideal balance to hectic and stressful modern lifestyles.

Style

Restorative yoga classes are very calm and slow-paced. These classes focus on the use of props to achieve restorative poses that calm and promote healing in the body.

A restorative yoga class will usually include only 5-8 poses that are held for longer periods of time; up to five minutes or longer. The purpose of these classes is to relax and rest.

The poses involved are calming and require minimal effort. Through longer holds, the objective of Restorative yoga is to stimulate healing processes within the nervous system.

Link to Optional Yoga Practice - Restorative Yoga | Stretch and Release to Savasana on YouTube (27:51).

1.7 Vinyasa yoga

23rd July 2025 at 4:58pm
vinyasa

Sanskrit

Vinyasa

Vi = sacred way

Asa = to place

Pronounce

VIN-yaa-saa

Benefits

Increased muscle strength, flexibility, cardiovascular function, respiratory capacity, and improved bone density.

Overview

Like Hatha Yoga, Vinyasa Yoga also has a wide definition and encompasses many different sub genres. Hatha Yoga will often hold a pose for several breaths, striving for a meditative state and perfecting a posture before moving into the next pose. Yin yoga involves holding a pose for several minutes. In contrast, Vinyasa Yoga is a ‘flow’ between poses.

Vinyasa classes also include breathing techniques that focus on the transition of the flow between poses. In Vinyasa, the synchronization of the breath and movement is an important part of the practice.

Ashtanga Yoga is a subcategory of Vinyasa and follows the same predefined sequence in every class. In contrast, Vinyasa maintains a flexible approach to the practice of yoga with a more creative class sequence.

Style

Vinyasa, often referred to as "Vinyasa Flow", focuses on the transition between poses. It also maintains a more rapid flow of movement through different postures.

The structure of Vinyasa flow will vary greatly from class to class since the definition of the style is so broad. Due to its faster class pace, many people are drawn to Vinyasa classes for its fitness applications.

Link to Optional Yoga Practice - Vinyasa Yoga | Surya Namaskar step by step on YouTube (5:40).

Link to more advanced Optional Yoga Practice - Vinyasa with Julie on YouTube (01:00:23)

1.8 Yin yoga

23rd July 2025 at 4:59pm

Sanskrit

The name Yin Yoga is rooted in Taoist philosophy from the Yin-Yang symbol which represents the feminine side.

Benefits

  • Increased flexibility, circulation, and concentration.
  • Improves mobility in the body and joints.
  • Improves the health of tissues, fascia, and joints.
  • Decreases anxiety and stress.

Overview

Yin Yoga was founded by Paulie Zink, who came from a background of martial arts and Taoist yoga.

In the 1970's, Zink introduced his students of martial arts into Yin Yoga, as he believed the flexibility drawn from it had suitable applications in the martial arts field.

It was further popularized by Paul Grilley who incorporated his knowledge of anatomy into the practice, and later by Sarah Powers who helped to bring today’s version of Yin Yoga mainstream.

Style

Yin Yoga provides a slower and more meditative style of yoga. In Yin, different poses are held for longer periods of time for a deeper stretch. In these classes, a pose is usually held for 1-2 minutes, but can sometimes be held for up to 5 minutes in duration.

The purpose of holding poses for long periods of time is to target the deeper tissues in our body; our connective tissue, ligaments, joints, and fascia. In Yin Yoga philosophy, it’s believed that by releasing our tissues in this way, we can improve and remove blocked Chi or energy in our body. Another benefit of Yin Yoga is that a static pose is a safer way to apply stress to the joints.

Yin Yoga is rooted in Taoist philosophy from the Yin-Yang symbol which represents the feminine side. Yin poses are still and calm poses that reach deeper muscle tissues. In contrast, yang poses are warmer and more energetic poses.

Yin Yoga is often a great compliment to high energy yang style classes that are most commonly seen in today's Western yoga classes. In Yin classes, there is no warm-up and the emphasis is put onto connective tissue rather than on the muscles. Because of this, the cues and format will be pretty different from Hatha styled classes.

The names of the asanas will also be different usually to draw attention to the fact that the approach to a certain posture is actually going to be different even though they may look similar. Gravity is usually going to be the biggest factor getting into a pose, rather than relying on the muscles.

Link to Optional Yoga Practice - Yin Yoga with Kate Lombardo on YouTube (01:0133).

2.1 Who Are You?

9th September 2025 at 12:49pm

Video 1 (15:47) discusses who we are:

  • Sat - eternal (our soul has always been)
  • Chit - full of knowledge
  • Ananda - blissful
  • Soul - in sanskrit is often referred to as Jiva, Atman, Purusha & Drastuh
In the Upanishad, the soul is said to be 1/1000th of the size of the tip of a hair, it resides in the heart but it illuminates the whole body

Lesson Recap

In this lesson we focus on the idea of the soul and that who we are is only one thing and one thing only:

All of us are an eternal SOUL.

Sat Chit Ananda.

Sat

There was never a time that we did not exist. We are eternal - we are Sat. Sat allows us see that right now, we are embodied. I am not this body any more than I am my shirt or my glasses. What this “Sat-ness” means is that I have a body and a mind BUT I am not those things. I am a soul. So who you are is actually Sat - eternal.

Chit

Chit allows us to fully know and realize that I am a soul embodied in a body. Having a full sense of awareness to your embodiment. I'm in this body. But I am not that body and that everything else except for the Soul is temporary. And the only thing that is eternal is this Soul. And it is that is the knowledge.

Ananda

The final of these three defining characters of the soul is Ananda which means blissful. Not just happy, not just content, not just “I’m okay” - truly in a state of bliss. We often spend so much time searching for happiness, looking for it outside of ourselves, when it is actually part of our natural state. The thing we are looking for, we already are.

In yoga philosophy, we use the term constitutional nature.

To be blissful is in our constitutional nature, we have simply forgotten it.

Luckily for us, the practices of yoga and the knowledge of yoga is all about waking us up to ourselves.

Reflections

  • How would my life be different if I truly embodied Sat Chit Ananda.
  • What challenges would evaporate? How would you view the world?
  • What if you really wrapped your mind around the notion that you're not your body and you're not in your mind, you're not the things that you have?
  • Who you are is a soul that is Sat (eternal) Chit (full of knowledge) Ananda (blissful), what would your life be like?

2.2 How the Mind Works (3 Parts of the Mind)

29th July 2025 at 4:35pm

Introduction

In this lesson we begin to explore the three parts of the mind - video 2 (15:06).

  • Manos - the lower mind, where our instincts reside
  • Ahankara - the false ego, our sense of identity that tries to tell us we are a body & a mind
  • Buddhi - the mind of intelligence and discernment, our ability to discern what is and is not us

If I am completely knowledgeable and every blissful, why don’t I know that?

The answer is the mind. From a yogic perspective, the mind and the brain are two different things.

It is said that the mind resides in the region of the brain. The soul resides in the region of the heart. The soul and the heart are two different things, just as the mind and the brain are two different things.

Manos

The first part, the lower part of the mind, is called the Manos mind. The Manos mind is where our instincts reside and where we learn to understand what it means to be hungry, to be thirsty, to be uncomfortable.

Ahankara

The second part of the mind is Ahankara which translates to the false ego. Ahankara is where we spend most of our time and from a yogic perspective, the ego means that false sense of identity.

The reason it's false is because it's a sense of identity that tells us “I am the body. I am the mind.” instead of “I have a body. I have a mind. What I am is a the Soul.”

Buddhi

The third part of the mind is the part where we DO want to live and that is called the Buddhi. The Buddhi is the mind of intelligence and discernment. In Sanskrit there is a word, Viveka, and it asks what is discerning? It is discerning what is not me to what is me.

B.K.S. Iyengar said that the asanas take the Buddhi mind and stretch it out across our bodies

Reflections

Take time to think about which of these three parts of the mind do you hang out in the most?

  • Do you find yourself going more by instinct a lot? And it is useful?
  • Do you have the power and the capacity to hang out in the Buddhi MInd?
  • Do you have the ability to make those discernments or do you get caught in the Ahankara? Do you get caught up in the false ego that says “I am just a body and I am just a mind”? The more we hang out there in that part of the mind, the less we are able to see who we truly are.
  • How can we cultivate more of our Buddhi mind so that it is ever present in our everyday lives?

2.3 How the Mind Works (Samskaras)

29th July 2025 at 4:36pm

This lesson continues our focus on the mind and we begin exploring just how malleable the mind is - video 3 (11:17).

Yoga philosophy teaches us that all of us are impressionable from a yogic perspective.

Our minds aren’t pieces of hard wood, they are more like a ball of clay.

Everything we see, taste, smell and experience through our senses makes an impression (samskara) on our mind.

And the word for those impressions in Sanskrit is Samskaras.

If everything makes an impression on our mind, a samskara, how do we deal with the problem that all things “good” or “bad” shape our mind.

We must ask ourselves - what kind of Samskara, what kind of impression am I making on me?

Lesson Recap

Our mind is so much more malleable than we realize and we have the power to change our minds as we see fit.

Samskaras encourage us to be just as mindful of what we are presenting in front of our minds daily because there are always going to be things we have seen that we don’t necessarily want. And we have the choice to not indulge those memories or thoughts.

Instead, we have the ability to turn our minds to the things we can control and I take in those impressions or thoughts.

Impressions and thoughts of loving, listening and peacefulness.

Reflections

  • What are some Samskaras are you putting in your mind?
  • What impressions are staying present in your mind?
  • Actively ask yourself - what am I changing my mind into?
  • There are things that may get there because of your environment- but remember, we have control about what we put in.

2.4 How the Mind Works (The Senses)

29th July 2025 at 4:36pm

Practical Example

  • I SEE (one of the senses) an advertisement for a pair of jeans and I get distracted
  • I SMELL coffee and I want some and I get distracted
  • I HEAR a nice song and I get distracted

In the jeans example, I see the jeans and I NEED them so I become attached to them, I'm obsessed by them and so I lust after them. Even if I get them they might:

  • not as good as I thought they were
  • they break or rip
  • someone else takes them or I lose them

Once these things happen I become angry and that anger has completely pulled us away from who we really are - we're now a body and a mind that needs this stuff, rather than an eternal, blissful soul.

Lesson Recap

In this lesson (video 4 - 12:26) Julie reviews how the mind works while moving through the senses.

An ancient analogy from arguably what is thought to be the first spiritual text, the Upanishads, is introduced referring to five horses as our five senses. Imagine five horses being out of control, pulling a chariot, and how the person in that driver’s seat would be falling from side to side. But luckily, that person is the one controlling the chariot and the reigns. This is how the Upanishad refers to the five senses.

Julie weaves this analogy into our work thus far - if the five senses are out of control, then they will drag us (and we are our soul) around. The soul is the person inside of the person steering the chariot - the chariot is your body. From the beginning these teachings say one must control the senses in order to be in full alignment with ourselves.

The consciousness flows in two directions, either OUT or IN. The senses pull our consciousness OUT into the world of THINGS.

A great analogy that Julie uses to describe the power that our senses can have on us is calling our five senses “weapons of mass distraction”. When we allow that distraction to take over our souls, it can fully derail us from our path and ourselves.

"While contemplating (thinking and thinking and thinking about) the objects of the senses, a person develops attachment for them, and from such attachment lust (desire) develops, and from lust anger arises."- Bhagavad Gita (2.62)

Julie shares another story from the Bhagad and continues to dive deeper into how the senses show up in our day to day life as well as how if affects our soul. When we allow the senses to take over, it can lead to our attachment of a thought, person or material position. Then lust creeps in and eventually anger.

Anger takes over due to the fact that we have become so very attached to this object or person or relationship that it has completely pulled us away from who we really are. The senses can create delusion which leads to Samskara after Samskara and spiraling down the rabbit hole away from our soul. And once again, we’ve completely forgotten that we are a soul.

It is important to develop a daily practice of being aware of our senses and the affects they have on our consciousness. That is how we bring these practices into our everyday lives.

Julie closes out this lesson with the importance of having the awareness to check in with ourselves and asking - when do I let my senses run away with me? We have all different senses that pull us away from our soul and drag us away from who we truly are. Whatever yours may be (sight, touch, smell, taste, etc.) feel it and notice.

Do you completely, without using any discernment from our Buddhi Mind, follow those senses down rabbit hole that take you away from your true self?

Or do you grab hold of the reins of the chariot? Yoga tells us to grab hold of the reins and steer.

3.1 Introduction to Anatomical Terminology

29th July 2025 at 4:40pm

What is anatomy?

Anatomy is the study of the structure of the human body:

  • What's there?
  • What are the parts of the body?
  • What do they look like?
  • What are they called?
A big part of anatomy is identifying and naming parts of the body but it's also important to remember that your body is an integrated whole. You’re not just a collection of separate parts rattling around inside your skin. Everything is connected, and all of the parts of the body work together in an integrated way.
  • Physiology refers to the study of the function of the body, typically on a cellular level.
  • Kinesiology is the study of how the body moves
  • Biomechanics applies the laws of physics to the movement of the body.

Why do we have to study anatomy?

  1. Anatomical language enables us to be clear and precise - understanding it will give you a way to analyze the position and movement of the body in a very clear way, so that you can then translate that understanding into ordinary language that your students will understand.
  2. This is the terminology that scientists and medical practitioners use to describe the human body. You may interact with medical practitioners at some point as a teacher, and it's useful to have an understanding of the language that they would use.
  3. Finally, if you look at an anatomy textbook or ask Google an anatomy question, you're going to find that those reference sources will use this anatomical language.

What does this section cover?

  • Anatomical Position & Planes of Movement
  • Terms of position
  • Terms of movement

3.2 Anatomical Position & Planes of Movement

29th July 2025 at 5:03pm

Anatomical position

All anatomical terms are in reference to anatomical position, which is tadasana (or mountain pose) with palms facing forward.

It's helpful for us to understand how parts of the body relate to each other, and how those relationships change when we move, no matter what position the body is in.

For instance, if I'm standing upright, clearly my head is on top and my feet are on the bottom. But what about if I’m in a headstand? What's on top and what's on the bottom then?

Having a reference position also helps us clarify movement of the body, because movements can be defined as moving away from that reference position or back toward it.

Why are the palms facing forward in anatomical position?

If you look at the skeleton, you can see that that there are two bones in the forearm.

  • One on the thumb side is called the radius
  • One on the little finger side is called the ulna

When you're standing with your palms facing forward, that lines up these two bones side by side. This lets us say that:

  • One of them is lateral, or to the side - the radius
  • One of them is medial or closer to the center line of the body - the ulna.
If you turn your palm so that it's facing backwards, that crosses the radius over the ulna. That makes it more difficult to say which one is on the inside and which one is on the outside. So having the palms facing forward just allows us to define the relationship between these two bones a little more clearly.

Planes of movement

  • Sagittal plane - Forward/backward movement
  • Frontal or coronal plane - Side to side movement
  • Transverse plane - Turning and rotational movements
Planes of movement are useful for analyzing and describing movement, but real-life movement doesn’t happen in a single cardinal plane - most movements in the body are multi-planar

But before we look at terms of movement, it will be helpful to understand the cardinal planes of the body:

Each of these planes are oriented 90 degrees to each other, so that they describe the three dimensions of space and divide a person into:

  1. a right half and a left half
  2. a front half and a back half
  3. a top half and a bottom half.

Think of the planes as not so much dividing in half (although they do this), but as constraints to a movement

Sagittal plane

The plane that divides the person into right and left halves is called the sagittal plane.

In this plane, forward and backward movement occurs.

Technically, this is the mid-sagittal plane, because it’s in the middle of the body, but any plane that’s parallel to that would also be in the sagittal plane.

Why is it called the sagittal plane?

Sagittal means arrow - think Sagittarius, the Archer. It's the plane in which you would shoot an arrow.

Frontal (coronal) plane

Divides the person into a front half and a back half - in this plane, we can move side to side. The frontal plane is also sometimes called the coronal plane.

In this plane, side to side movement occurs

Why is it called the frontal plane?

The word corona means crown. Imagine if I were wearing a tiara, like a crown running over the top of my head from right to left, or you could picture a set of headphones running over the top of my head. That plane of the tiara or the headphones would define the coronal plane.

Transverse plane

​​The word transverse means running across, or horizontally. So it's the plane that's running horizontally in the illustration, dividing the person into a top half and a bottom half. This plane is parallel to the floor or the ceiling if you’re standing upright.

In this plane, twisting or rotational movement occurs

If that's not clear, imagine a clock face on the floor beneath me. The hands of the clock would be moving within the transverse plane. So if turn to the right, or clockwise, or the left, or counter-clockwise, those movements are in the transverse plane.

These planes of movement are useful for analyzing and describing movement. They allow us to name the movements of the body precisely, in relationship to an abstract three-dimensional space. But it’s important to remember that this is just a conceptual framework. It’s useful, but real life movements rarely happen in a single cardinal plane.

We don't move like robots - most movements that we make are multi-planar. In other words, most of the time we move within multiple planes at once.

3.3 Terms of Movement

29th July 2025 at 4:42pm

In this video we look at the most common terms of movement in the:

  • Saggital plane
  • Frontal plane
  • Transverse plane

This is NOT a comprehensive list of movement terms - later we will look at more specialised terms of movement for specific body parts.

Saggital Plane

Flexion and Extension

Remember, we can move forward and backward in the sagittal plane.

The general terms of movement in the sagittal plane are flexion and extension:

  • Flexion - Bending e.g. the elbow (technically, decreasing the angle of a joint) in the saggital plane)
  • Extension - Straightening e.g. the elbow. If a joint is flexed, extension means coming back to anatomical position. (Note some joints allow extension past anatomical position)

When we describe movements in terms of a body part, for instance, flexing the forearm, we’re generally assuming that the

  • part closer to the center of the body remains still and the
  • part farther from the center of the body is the one that’s moving.

In other words, flexing my thigh would mean bringing my thigh closer to the front of my pelvis. The thigh is considered the moveable part, while the pelvis and trunk are considered to be the stationary part.

There’s nothing wrong with calling this movement flexing the thigh, but I think it’s clearer to say that I’m flexing my hip joint. That’s the joint between the pelvis and the thigh where the movement occurs. That helps make it clear that if I bend my pelvis and trunk forward from my hip joints, as in uttanasana, that’s also hip flexion.

Extension past anatomical position

The term extension also gets a little more complicated because in many joints in the body, we actually are able to extend past anatomical position, or past straight. For instance, the hip joint can extend past anatomical position.

If I’m starting with my hip flexed, with my thigh up towards my chest, and then bring that leg back to a standing position, I'm extending or, straightening, my hip. But if I keep going in the same direction, you can see that I can take my thigh backward behind my pelvis, extending the hip past anatomical position. This is part of the normal range of motion of the hip.

This movement past anatomical position is sometimes called hyperextension, but in yoga hyperextension is usually reserved for a different type of movement

Frontal plane

Remember, we can move side to side in the frontal plane.

  • Abduction - Moving a limb out to the side, away from the midline
  • Adduction - Moving a limb toward the midline
  • Lateral flexion - Side bending (right or left)

One way to remember is abduction also means kidnapping or taking away

so ABDUCTION is moving AWAY from the midline

What's the midline?

The midline is a line drawn down the front of the body that would divide me into right half and a left half.

So, draw a line between my eyes, through my nostrils, and continue that line all the way down to the floor, between my feet. That's the midline.

  • If I move my arm out to the side, away from the midline of my body, that's called shoulder, or arm, abduction
  • If I move my arm toward the midline of the body, that's called shoulder, or arm, adduction
  • If I move my thigh away from the midline of the body, that's hip abduction
  • If I move thigh toward the midline, that's hip adduction

Extension past anatomical position

In the same way that you can extend many joints past anatomical position, you can also adduct the shoulder and hip joints past anatomical position.

For instance, I can adduct my arm past anatomical position and cross it over to the other side. Of course my trunk is in the way, so I have to couple that with a little bit of shoulder flexion, or a little bit of shoulder extension if I bring the arm back behind me.

What about the spine?

Well, the spine is the midline, so it doesn't really make sense to talk about abducting or adducting the spine. Instead, we refer to frontal plane movement of the spine as lateral flexion, which just means side bending.

I can laterally flex, or side bend, my spine to the right or to the left.

Transverse plane

Remember, rotational or twisting in the transverse plane.

  • External (or lateral) rotation - Rotating the front of a limb away from the midline
  • Internal (or medial) rotation - Rotating the front of a limb toward the midline
  • Axial rotation - Rotating the trunk (right or left)
  • Horizontal abduction - Combined flexing and abducting a limb
  • Horizontal adduction - Combined flexing and adducting a limb

3.4 Terms of Position

29th July 2025 at 4:43pm

Terms of position

  • Anterior - Toward the front of the body
  • Posterior - Toward the back of the body
  • Superior - Above or higher than another part of the body
  • Inferior - Below or lower than another part of the body
  • Lateral - Toward the side of the body
  • Medial - Toward the middle of the body
  • Proximal - Nearer to the point of attachment of a limb or the trunk of the body
  • Distal - Farther from the point of attachment of a limb or the trunk of the body
  • Superficial - Closer to the surface of the body
  • Deep - Farther from the surface of the body

These are terms of position. We use these terms to describe the location of one part of the body in relationship to another part.

4.1 The Six Principles of Yoga Alignment

7th September 2025 at 6:43pm

Overview

As a yoga teacher, your role is to help your students get in and out of yoga poses safely.

It's easy to get injured in a yoga pose, especially if we don't understand the basic principles of alignment in yoga.

Injuries occur when students don't work within the limits of their own bodies and push themselves too far.

Another common reason why students get injured is when they focus on how they think a pose should look or compare how their pose looks to other students.

It's important to keep in mind that each pose will look different from student to student. How a pose looks is based on different variables including;

  • activity level
  • practice level
  • years they've been practicing
  • body shape
  • bone shape
  • bone size
  • genetics
  • flexibility, etc.

The best practice is to have your students focus on how the pose feels in their own bodies vs. how it looks.

Here are six key foundations of yoga alignment to help guide students in their yoga practice.

Six Key Foundations Of Alignment

1. Hands

It's important to protect students against wrist strain and injury, especially when the hands are on the mat and bearing weight.

  • Instruct your students to spread their fingers wide on their mat to distribute their body weight evenly throughout their fingers, wrists, and palms
  • Another teaching cue is to press through the thumb and forefingers (or pointer fingers) which will create a natural lift upwards of the arches in the palms
  • When the arches are naturally lifted in this way, our body weight is distributed evenly to protect hands and wrists.

2. Feet

To create a firm foundation in the feet for standing yoga poses, we want to make sure we're distributing weight evenly through our ankles, toes, and feet.

Doing this also ensures that surrounding joints such as our knees and hips are also protected. Here are some tips to achieve this:

  • Spread the toes evenly onto the mat. This allows the weight in our feet to be distributed evenly and prevents the feet from lifting up off the mat.
  • Press through the ball and heel of the feet evenly. With the exception of Chair pose, in most standing poses it's important to have a firm foundation in the feet. By pressing into our heels and balls of our feet, we are firmly rooted to the mat - giving us support and stability in standing poses
  • Feel the natural lift upwards of the arches in the feet
  • Press evenly through all four corners of the feet.

The two cues help to create firmness and stability in the feet.

3. Knees

In any standing or balance poses, we want to avoid locking the knee by keeping a soft microbend in the knees. This helps to protect the knees from injury and keeps our legs stabilized.

In standing poses, the knees should:

  • be stacked directly over the ankles or a little bit before the ankle to avoid injury.
  • not go past the ankles - you should be able to see your toes when you look down
  • kept in the same direction as the toes - this prevents the knees from splaying out to either side or rotating inwards or outwards.

In standing poses where strength in the legs is needed, we can engage the stronger muscles in our legs to take strain off the knees.

One way to do this is to instruct students to feel their kneecaps lift up slightly to engage the quad muscles.

4. Shoulders

In many yoga poses, it's common to see students have their shoulders up by their ears. Doing this can create stress and injury in the neck, shoulders, and spine.

An excellent teaching cue for students is to keep their shoulders drawn down away from their ears.

Another way you could say this to students is to roll the shoulders down the back of the spine.

5. Spine

Spine alignment is an integral part of any safe yoga practice. Ways to protect the spine and maintain alignment include:

  • engaging the core muscles. By engaging the core muscles, it helps to take strain off our lower backs - a vulnerable injury prone area in our spine
  • focus on keeping their spine elongated by pulling the crown of their head up towards the sky and at the same time pointing their tailbone down towards the mat. This helps to create a feeling of lengthening in the body and keeps the spine straight.

When it comes to poses that involve twisting of the spine, always work to keep the spine aligned and allow the twist to come from the core. Begin with the twist in the core and then allow the head and neck follow last.

In poses that involve folds, always allow the fold to start at the hips instead of the lower back. In forward folds, the focus should be on lengthening the spine first before fully folding forward.

6. Core

Engaging the core can protect the lower back and hips from injury.

Help students transition in and out of poses by bringing awareness to their abdominal muscles. To do this, you can

  • instruct students to pull their belly into their spine. This automatically creates stability in the body and also contracts the core muscles
  • say to students "engage the core" or "activate the core." Core engagement also keeps students stable during balance poses.

4.2 The Five Bandhas of Yoga

7th September 2025 at 7:43pm

In yoga, there are five Bandhas which are believed to lock in and control energy in the body.

In ancient Sanskrit, the word 'Bandha' means to tighten or lock. Understanding and using the Bandhas can help to support and boost our asana practice.

  1. Bandhas help to flow an increase of blood to our organs and promote detoxification in the body.
  2. Bandhas also help to relieve tension and stress in the body, supporting our mental and emotional health.
  3. Bandhas are also believed to support and clear our chakra centers from blocked energy.
  4. Bandhas can be useful in teaching your students yoga foundations for a safe practice.
  5. Bandhas are also helpful in creating body awareness and for fulfilling a spiritual aspect to a yoga practice.

Teaching Bandhas in your classes are optional depending on your class setting and your preference as a teacher.

1. Hasta Bandha or Hand Lock

Hasta Bandha is believed to draw energy up from the palms of the hands to energize and support the arms and shoulders in weight bearing poses.

Hasta Bandha also establishes a good foundation for when our hands are on the mat in poses such as Downward Facing Dog or Chaturanga. To achieve Hasta Bandha, spread the fingers wide on the mat. Press down evenly through the fingers, palms, and wrists. This movement allows the inner arches of the palms to naturally lift up. It also balances our body weight in hands, wrists, arms, and shoulders.

Practice:

  1. Begin in a Table Top position. Keep your shoulders directly over your wrists and allow your spine to remain lengthened.
  2. Spread your fingers wide and press down evenly through your palms, fingers, and wrists.
  3. Feel energy rising up from the palms of your hands and flowing up to your wrists, arms, and shoulders.

2. Pada Bandha or Foot Lock

Pada Bandha is believed to draw energy up from the soles of the feet to energize and support the legs in standing poses.

This Bandha also establishes a good foundation for standing yoga poses and helps to keep us stabilized on our feet. To achieve this Bandha, spread the toes and press down evenly through the ball and heel of the feet. This movement allows the inner arches of the feet to naturally lift up. It also balances our body weight in our legs, feet, and ankles.

Another way to achieve this Bandha, is to lift the toes slightly up in standing poses. This also creates a natural lift of the inner arches in the feet.

Practice:

  1. Begin in Mountain pose (tadasana).
  2. Root down through all four corners of your feet and feel energy begin to rise up through the soles of your feet.
  3. Feel that energy rise through your legs, up through your spine, and to the crown of your head.

3. Mula Bandha or Root Lock

Mula bandha is believed to draw energy upwards in the body from our pelvic area.

This Bandha is focused on the pelvic area and is similar to a Kegel exercise. In this Bandha, we use the same muscles we would use if we were going to the bathroom.

  • For women to find this Bandha, contract the muscles at the bottom of the pelvic floor.
  • For men, to find this Bandha, contract the area between the testes and anus.

The benefits of this Bandha is for pain or tension relief in the pelvic area. It is also believed to have healing benefits for optimal sexual and reproductive health.

Practice:

  1. Begin in Easy pose. Root down evenly through your sit bones.
  2. Feel the earth and ground beneath you supporting your body.
  3. Gently contract your pelvic area as you visualize energy begin to radiate and rise up in your body.
  4. Allow that energy to flow upwards toward the crown of your head.

4. Jalandhara Bandha or Throat Lock

Jalandhara Bandha is believed to draw in and stimulate energy in the throat and chest area.

This Bandha also helps to protect the neck during supine yoga pose - when the chin is slightly tucked into the chest, it creates lengthen and space in the neck area; helping to relieve tension in the neck and spine.

Jalandhara Bandha also helps to draw energy into the chest and may be used during breathing or pranayama exercises that require retention of the breath. To achieve this Bandha, tuck the chin slightly into the chest. Contract the neck slightly as you feel length and space in the shoulders and neck.

Jalandhara Bandha is believed to calm the mind and nerves.

Practice:

  1. Come into Bridge pose.
  2. Draw your chin slightly into your chest as you lift your chest and peel your hips up off the ground.
  3. Feel energy radiating downwards into your chest area as you lift and open the chest up.
  4. Allow that energy to flow and activate down to your core.

5. Uddiyana Bandha or Core Lock

Uddiyana Bandha refers to engaging the abdominal muscles for breath retention and drawing energy upward in the body from the core.

Traditionally, this Bandha is practiced in seated postures to support breathing exercises. Because Uddiyana Bandha focuses on contracting the core, it can also be utilized to create stability in the body in standing poses, core focused poses, and balance poses.

To practice Uddiyana Bandha traditionally, begin by sitting in Easy pose and inhale. After you exhale, tuck the core into the spine and hold. Release the core and come back to an inhale. Repeat.

This can be practiced at the beginning of a class to create energy and heat in the body. Due to the contraction of the belly, this Bandha should only be practiced on an empty stomach.

Practice:

  1. Begin in a Boat pose variation that is comfortable for you.
  2. Draw your belly in towards your spine and activate your core.
  3. Feel energy radiating from your core and drawing upwards into your body.

4.4 Yoga Asanas Introduction

9th September 2025 at 4:37pm

Introduction

In the Yoga Sutras by Patanjali, asana is referred in Sutra 2.46 – Sthira Sukham Asanam. This sutra can be translated as: 'Asana is a steady, comfortable posture'

translation by yoga teacher and guru Sri Swami Satchidananda.

Ancient yogis defined health and fitness not as being able to hold or master a posture, but rather as:

  • being structurally stable
  • having the ability to move with grace and ease
  • the elimination of suffering
  • the ability to withstand change.

​Asanas are one of the most recognized parts of yoga in the modern world today. Asanas help us to bridge the gap between our breath, our mind, and our bodies.

They serve as constant reminders to bring ourselves back to the present moment. Through Asana practice, we not only evolve physically, but we also notice the subtle inner effects it has on our minds and inner peace.

As we practice difficult poses, we can learn to master confidence, inner strength, and resilience.

Through restorative poses, we learn to come back to our inner stillness, quiet the fluctuations of the mind, and surrender to the present moment.

As a teacher, your role in asana practice is to guide your students through a beautifully orchestrated journey of breath, movement, and alignment. Through your words and guidance, you will help your students safely get in and out of poses. Through your creative sequencing and teaching cues, you help to create an enriching class experience for them.

Through your presence and by teaching from the heart, you will inspire a space for your students to evolve and grow.

Review each asana pose several times and take time to memorize the different teaching and alignment cues for each. Some other suggestions are working with a friend or fellow yogi to practice the poses and alignment together.

It always helps to begin scripting out cues for each pose and rehearse them regularly. Over time and with practice, you will gain confidence in being able to guide your students in their asana practice.

Keep in mind that the wording for the teaching cues we offer for each pose are merely guidelines. Feel free to add in your own creative wording for cues as you see fit or you can use them directly as we have provided for you.

A great teacher always brings out his or her own authentic voice while teaching, so feel free to modify or adjust our language so that it suits you.

Asana Benefits

Some of the many reported benefits of asana include:

  1. Release mental and physical tension.
  2. Prepare the body for seated meditation.
  3. Mobilize and stabilize the body.
  4. Promote balance, strength and flexibility.
  5. Explore.
  6. Release “excess stuff.”
  7. Direct attention inward.
  8. Feel more deeply connected with all of life.
  9. Experience meditation flowing spontaneously.
  10. Balance the energies and forces throughout the body.
  11. Reduce stress.
  12. Increase concentration.
  13. Open energy channels.
  14. Integrate mind and body.
  15. Release impurities.
  16. Increase awareness.

Eight limbs

13th June 2025 at 7:43pm
ashtangaeightlimbspantanjali

Patanjali’s system is known as the Eight Limbed Path.

Each limb builds upon the last and supports holistic growth—physically, mentally, and spiritually.

The first two limbs describe how we act towards others and ourselves. The next three limbs describe how to prepare our body. The final three limbs show we we prepare or mind.
  • Yamas - moral restrictions or discipline (how we treat others)
  • Niyamas - positive observances (how we treat ourselves)
  • Asanas - physical postures (originally seat for meditation)
  • Pranayama - breath control
  • Pratayahara - sense withdrawal
  • Dharana - concentration
  • Dhyana - meditation
  • Samadhi - enlightenment
Yogi's need always to practise poses diligently daily –> Samadhi

This is the philosophical heart of the yoga journey

not just movement, but transformation.

Origins of Yoga

1st July 2025 at 3:17pm

Yoga didn’t emerge from one single source—it grew from many spiritual traditions over centuries.

While most strongly associated with Hinduism, the roots of yoga are intertwined with Jainism and Buddhism as well. It’s important to recognize this multi-lineage origin and to approach yoga’s history with reverence and a willingness to continually learn.

The earliest known references to yoga are found in The Vedas, a collection of sacred texts written between 1700–1100 BCE. These ancient writings form the foundation of Hindu philosophy and include hymns, rituals, and guidance for living in alignment with spiritual truth.

The Sanskrit word yoga means “to yoke” or “to unite”—specifically, the union of the individual self (Atman) with the universal spirit (Brahman).

Atman - SELF - the individual soul or inner essence

Braham - UNIVERSAL SPIRIT - the infinite, eternal universal spirit

From the beginning, yoga was seen as a spiritual discipline

aimed at transcending the ego and connecting with something greater.

Spiritual well-being

20th June 2025 at 5:09pm

What does Spiritual well-Being Mean?

Spiritual well-being refers to a sense of purpose, meaning, and connection in life that is rooted in personal values, beliefs, and principles. It is not limited to religious practices or affiliations—though it can include them—but encompasses a broader search for meaning and harmony, both within oneself and in relation to the world

Key Aspects of Spiritual Well-Being

Purpose and Meaning

Spiritual well-being is fundamentally about finding and expanding a sense of purpose and meaning in life. This may involve clarifying personal values, exploring what matters most, and striving to live in alignment with those values

Connection

It often includes a feeling of connection—to oneself, to others, to nature, or to something greater than oneself (which could be a higher power, the universe, or a sense of community)

Inner Peace and Harmony

Spiritual well-being is associated with achieving inner peace, harmony, and balance. It provides an anchor during life's challenges and helps individuals cope with uncertainty, loss, or stress

Practices

While some people express spiritual well-being through religious rituals, prayer, or meditation, others may find it through mindfulness, time in nature, creative pursuits, or acts of service.

Personal Growth

It involves ongoing self-reflection, the development of compassion, forgiveness, and altruism, and the pursuit of goals that foster optimism and hope.

Not Necessarily Religious
Spiritual well-being does not require religious belief.

It is about the universal human need for meaning, purpose, and connection, which can be met in many different ways

Benefits of Spiritual Well-Being:

  • Greater resilience and ability to cope with stress
  • Increased sense of belonging and community
  • Improved mental and physical health
  • Enhanced capacity for love, forgiveness, and creativity
  • Motivation to contribute to the greater good

In Summary

Spiritual well-being is the dimension of wellness that helps individuals find meaning, purpose, and connection in life.

It is deeply personal, can be expressed in many forms, and plays a vital role in overall health and happiness—regardless of religious belief

Tantra

20th June 2025 at 5:26pm
ashtangatantra

Another important thread in the philosophy of yoga is the concept of Tantra—which often gets misunderstood in the West.

At its core, tantra views the entire universe as sacred or an expression of the divine.

Everything you touch, feel, and experience is a doorway into divine consciousness.

Rather than escaping the world to find enlightenment, tantra teaches that the divine is already here—in your body, your breath, your relationships, and your practice.

From the root word tan, meaning “expansive” or “whole,” tantra recognizes the entire fabric of existence as an expression of the divine feminine, or Shakti energy.

The idea is to open up to a sense of the divine within any experience. The philosophy of tantra identifies the path of freedom not through renunciation of human desire and experience, but indeed largely through it.

Instead of transcending the material reality of human experience, going more intensely into it is the path to enlightenment and happiness.

In the ninth century CE, the Vijnana Bhairava offered a rich array of simple-to-complex practices for tapping into this quality of awareness. More recently, tantric yogis have expanded this to offer what Daniel Odier refers to as “micro-practices.”

The micro-practices are based on the fact that the mind is very fast, likes to be fast, and is good at it. The ancient yogis had a wonderful idea: to invent a practice that goes just as fast as the mind. Rather than trying to counteract the mind, one goes with it for a brief moment in which one tries to be completely present to something very simple.

Sitting with your morning coffee, you pass the cup beneath your nose, and for a moment you are fully absorbed in all the sensations you are experiencing. Walking in the woods, your foot crosses over a dry leaf while a light breeze caresses your skin and damp forest aromas flow into your olfactory senses. There you are, in those few seconds, completely present to your senses of sound, light, aroma, your skin, your heart, and a sense of something far greater that is in it all, you and nature and spirit as one.

The aim is to be fully present in just that moment, just that one breath, finding there a sense of being in a state of bliss or oneness.

Bringing this into yoga asana and pranayama practices, a far more refined and subtle quality of awareness arises, lending a more nuanced body-breath-mind connection, a more expansive consciousness of the wholeness. At the heart of this practice is being present when you breathe in and out, bringing consciousness to the breath and feeling that you are breathing completely, letting go of the breath completely, and in that space feeling the body-mind going to a place of spontaneous awareness of spirit or bliss.

The Bhagavad Gita (Song of God)

13th June 2025 at 7:04pm
bhagavadgita

The Bhagavad Gita (or “Song of God”), a 700-verse Hindu scripture written around 200-100 BCE, is part of the larger epic, the Mahabharata.

It is a powerful dialogue between the warrior Arjuna and the deity Krishna, who serves as his spiritual guide.

On the brink of battle, Arjuna is overwhelmed by doubt and fear. Krishna’s teachings reveal how one can live and act in alignment with truth, even amidst chaos.

In the Gita (Bhagavad Gita), three primary paths of yoga are explained:

  • Karma Yoga – the path of selfless service - ACTION
  • Jnana Yoga – the path of wisdom and knowledge - CONTEMPLATION
  • Bhakti Yoga – the path of devotion and love for the divine - DEVOTION

These paths reflect that yoga is not one-size-fits-all. Whether through action, contemplation, or devotion, each person can choose the route that resonates most with their nature.

The divine lives within you, and that inner awareness is the gateway to enlightenment

In summary, the Bhagavad Gita advocates for a balanced approach to spiritual growth, emphasizing the practice of yoga to control desires, escape the cycle of rebirth (samsara) and the fulfillment of one's dharma.

Through yoga, one can achieve a state of liberation (moksha) and transcend the material world.

This is in contrast to the complete renunciation of action as in the ascetic ideal. Ascetics believe that by withdrawing from the world and its attachments, they can free themselves from the cycle of rebirth.

The Upanishads

13th June 2025 at 6:58pm
upanishad

Upanishads - sitting down beside

As time passed, the Upanishads, (composed around 800–200 BCE) offered a more philosophical and inward approach. These texts are considered the culmination of Vedic thought and lay the groundwork for many of yoga’s core principles.

Here, we’re introduced to two key concepts:

  • Atman – the individual soul or inner essence
  • Brahman – the infinite, eternal universal spirit

The goal of spiritual practice, according to the Upanishads, is to realize that:

Atman is Brahman and Brahman is Atman

The divine lives within you, and that inner awareness is the gateway to enlightenment.

The Vedas

13th June 2025 at 6:56pm
veda

Vedas - knowledge

The Vedas, sometimes collectively called the Veda, are a large body of religious texts originating in ancient India and written between 1700–1100 BCE.

Composed in Vedic Sanskrit, the texts constitute the oldest layer of Sanskrit literature and are considered to be the oldest scriptures of Hinduism.

Within the Vedas, which means knowledge, meditation was the central tool for spiritual growth. Each Veda contains different types of texts, including hymns, rituals, and philosophical discussions.

The four Vedas are the:

  • Rigveda
  • Yajurveda
  • Samaveda
  • Atharvaveda

The Rig Veda, the oldest of the four Vedas, includes hymns that were chanted or repeated as mantras

These sacred sounds were believed to carry vibrational power that could elevate consciousness and lead to spiritual insight.

Yamas

20th June 2025 at 5:16pm
ashtangayamas

Restraints or moral disciplines

The first of the eight limbs - how you behave towards others within society

  • Ahimsa (non-harming in thought, word or action. Himsa means pain so ahimsa means no pain)
  • Satya (truthfulness or honesty)
  • Asteya (non-stealing)
  • Brahmacharya (wise use of energy, including sexual energy, living with moderation)
  • Aparigraha (non-hoarding, non-attachment or non-possessiveness)

Ahimsa

The word ‘Himsa’ can be translated as pain, whereas ‘Ahimsa’ translates to ‘not causing pain’ or compassion.

The term nonviolence is typically associated with this principle however the word nonviolence can be rather misleading as it may suggest dramatic or physical harm.

Ahimsa is not restricted to physical harm and is meant to depict compassion across all living things.

Ahimsa provides a foundation for the rest of the Yamas because it can contextualize different circumstances.

For example, the following principle is Satya or Truthfulness. Truthful statements can be delivered in a way which harms others which would work in conflict with Ahimsa. In order to truly practice truthfulness in a fulfilling manner, compassion needs to be in place.

Satya

Satya is the principle of truthfulness - being honest with ourselves and others.

Patanjali outlines truthfulness as a means to freedom, making a connection between living an honest life and being free from fear.

A clear conscious is an important aspect of maintaining a clear mind. Honesty can be done externally with others, or internally with ourselves. With compassion, honesty can be practiced in a meaningful way that provides freedom from guilt or dishonesty.

A question sometimes arises over the possible conflict between this second principle and ahimsa. What if the truth hurts? In the ancient epic Mahabharata, this apparent conundrum is carefully navigated: “Truth should be told when agreeable, should be said agreeably, and truth should not be said that does harm; however, never lie to give pleasure.”

Asteya

The essence of asteya, “not stealing,” is freeing oneself from the desire to have something that one has not earned or paid for. It doesn't just mean taking something that doesn't belong to you - it means earning things.

Listing greed as one of the “seven spiritual sins,” Gandhi emphasized that “wealth without work” is wrong.

Brahmacharya

The essence of this sutra is honoring yourself and others in intimate relationships. It is typically given loose interpretation as the “right use of energy.”

Brahmacharya roughly means "to stay true to one's Self or one own Atma" or "on the path of Brahman".

Brahmacharya, a discipline of controlling the senses, is seen as a way to liberation. Though sexual restraint is a part of brahmacharya, brahmacharya encompasses all striving toward a passionless state.

Aparigraha

Aparigraha means “non-covetousness” —not being greedy, or being free of desire, is how this is traditionally interpreted.

It is about living with generosity of spirit and action, giving without expecting something in return.

Applied to asana and pranayama, this principle can help students approach their practice with an attitude of patience in which steadiness and ease is more important than getting into a pose.

Finding a Seat - 5 Seated Yoga Postures

Instructor

Patrick - YouTube link

Purpose of the practice

What does it mean to "Take a comfortable cross-legged seat?

In yoga, the Sanskrit word asana is often translated as POSE, but another translation of asana is SEAT.

Some believe that practicing the asanas or poses is actually preparation for the yoga practitioner to find a comfortable cross-legged seat.

This comfortable position then allows them to perform the higher states of yoga such as pranyama and meditation. The poses are all designed to make the body strong and flexible so that when we sit down on the ground, our body is relaxed and we can work on the breath and the mind.

Tips

  • Some people may need blocks, cushions or blankets to raise their hips so that their legs can relax
  • Hip creases (where your leg bones and your pelvis meet) should be a little bit higher than your knees.
  • When your legs relax your spine can elongate
  • When your spine elongates your body is in a restful place and your mind is a free and open
  • This allows you to allow it to work on the more introspective aspects of yoga practice like pranayama and meditation

Poses

  1. Suhkasana - Easy set
  2. Sidhasana - Divine seat
  3. Virasana - Hero pose
  4. Padmasana - Lotus pose
  5. Seated chair pose

Pose 1 - Sukhasana (Easy seat)

Seat should be symmetrical and comfortable so our legs can relax and our spine can lift up
  1. Start in dandasana (Stiff rod pose)
  2. Bend legs and cross right shin over left right in the middle to create an X
  3. Let your knees relax (drop) so that they're resting on top of your feet
  4. Make sure that your shins are parallel to the front of your mat and your feet are underneath your knees
  5. Put your hands down by your sides, gently press down, lift your chest up and relax your legs
Try to alternate the crossing of the legs between practice sessions to improve symmetry of your leg bones and pelvis

Yoga Sutras of Pantanjali

20th June 2025 at 3:58pm

Fast forward to around 200 CE, when the sage Patanjali compiled The Yoga Sutras—a foundational text in classical yoga.

The Sutras are a collection of 196 short verses (sutras means “threads”) that offer a blueprint for spiritual development.

Many students and teachers are surprised that these writings contain no mention of a singular pose or the physical postures as we think of them today, they lay the philosophical and psychological groundwork for the practice.

Patanjali defines yoga as:

Yogas chitta vritti nirodha

Yoga is the stilling of the fluctuations of the mind.

In other words, yoga is about calming the inner chatter so we can access the truth of who we really are.

Patanjali’s system is known as the Eight Limbed Path or Eight limbs.

Each limb builds upon the last and supports holistic growth—physically, mentally, and spiritually.
